{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516793"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:46:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:46:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583718"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:26:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:26:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12715"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.79,0.11,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5170"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105803"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5170"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88272"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"2196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4534"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10500"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43347"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105803"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic after his blood pressure was found to be 160/100 mmHg at a routine check at his local pharmacy. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus. He does not take any regular medications other than metformin, which he finds difficult to remember to take regularly. He is an active smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 162/96 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine dipstick: negative for red blood cells, positive for protein\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine albumin-creatinine ratio: 35 mg/mmol (0-3.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHbA1c: 8.0% (4.0-5.6)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment for this patient\u0027s hypertension?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atenolol","Perindopril","Amlodipine","Hydrochlorothiazide","Eplerenone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hypertension, poorly controlled type 2 diabetes mellitus, and evidence of chronic kidney disease (CKD) with macroalbuminuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe decision to commence antihypertensive medication should be guided by a patient\u0027s absolute cardiovascular disease (CVD) risk, in conjunction with accurate blood pressure measurements.\u00a0According to the current Australian guidelines for hypertension management (2016), for patients at high absolute CVD risk (\u0026gt;10% over five years), or those with existing CVD, diabetes with microalbuminuria (as in this patient) or moderate to severe chronic kidney disease (CKD) (also likely to be the case in this patient), antihypertensive therapy should be considered regardless of BP levels, as these conditions elevate the risk of cardiovascular events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E, an ACE inhibitor, is the most appropriate first-line treatment for this patient. ACE inhibitors are the preferred initial therapy for hypertension in patients with diabetes and microalbuminuria because they provide renoprotection by reducing proteinuria and slowing CKD progression. They also have beneficial effects on cardiovascular outcomes. A target blood pressure of below 120/90 mmHg should be aimed for in patients with diabetes with microalbuminuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtenolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, can be useful in blood pressure management for CKD patients, but it is not considered first-line treatment. Beta-blockers are particularly beneficial in patients with coronary artery disease or heart failure, which are not mentioned in this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E, a calcium channel blocker, may be used as an alternative or adjunctive therapy in patients with CKD who cannot tolerate or have contraindications to ACE inhibitors. However, it is not the preferred first-line therapy in this patient population, especially in the presence of significant proteinuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E, a thiazide diuretic, is not a first-line management option for hypertension in CKD but can be an effective adjunctive therapy, especially if the patient shows signs of fluid overload. It is most effective when eGFR is \u0026gt;45 mL/min/1.73m2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEplerenone\u003C/strong\u003E, a mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist, can reduce proteinuria and slow CKD progression in patients with hypertension. However, it is not the preferred first-line therapy and carries a risk of hyperkalaemia, especially when used in combination with ACE inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that patients with CKD and hypertension often require multiple agents for adequate blood pressure control. The choice of additional agents should consider the patient\u0027s comorbidities and overall cardiovascular risk profile. In this case, addressing the patient\u0027s poorly controlled diabetes and smoking cessation would also be crucial parts of the management plan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ACE inhibitors are the first-line treatment for hypertension in patients with chronic kidney disease and proteinuria.","Patients with chronic kidney disease and hypertension often require multiple agents for adequate blood pressure control.","Antihypertensive choices should consider the patient\u0027s comorbidities and cardiovascular risk profile."],"references":["Kidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes (KDIGO) Blood Pressure Work Group. KDIGO 2021 Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Blood Pressure in Chronic Kidney Disease. Kidney Int. 2021 Mar;99(3S):S1-S87. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33637192/","Gabb GM, Mangoni AA, Anderson CS, Cowley D, Dowden JS, Golledge J, Hankey GJ, Howes FS, Leckie L, Perkovic V, Schlaich M, Zwar NA, Medley TL, Arnolda L. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults - 2016. Med J Aust. 2016 Jul 18;205(2):85-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27456450/","Howes F, Hansen E, Nelson M. Management of hypertension in general practice--a qualitative needs assessment of Australian GPs. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 May;41(5):317-23. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22558624/","Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care. In: Kidney Health Australia, Melbourne [online]. 2020. Available at: https://nacchocommunique.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/chronic-kidney-disease-management-in-primary-care-4th-edition-handbook.pdf","National Heart Foundation of Australia. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults \u2013 2016 [Internet]. Melbourne: National Heart Foundation of Australia; 2016 [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://assets.contentstack.io/v3/assets/blt8a393bb3b76c0ede/bltbf3d36e10b48f01f/65b0963ea933e532ae0286de/01_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf","Atkins ER, Perkovic V. Blood pressure: at what level is treatment worthwhile?. Aust Prescr 2019;42:127-30. Available at: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2019.038"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88272"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12715"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88272"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:30:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T09:30:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5170"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105803"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","li